# Parallel Project Rule — Zero-Burden Priority

## Core Product Principle

Rotation is for distributing unavoidable inconvenience, not for creating inconvenience when a fully comfortable shared time already exists.

If there is at least one valid meeting time where:
- no participant violates a hard no-time boundary
- all participants are within working hours
- total burden is zero
- max individual burden is zero

then the scheduler MUST choose from that zero-burden candidate set first.

The system must never manufacture inconvenience for the sake of rotation or fairness when a fully comfortable shared option already exists.

---

## Required Scheduling Behavior

### 1. Zero-burden candidates always win
Before fairness spread, beam ranking, topK pruning, or fallback selection can choose an inconvenient slot, the scheduler must first detect whether zero-burden candidates exist.

If zero-burden candidates exist:
- selection must be restricted to the zero-burden subset
- fairness logic may only be used as a deterministic tie-breaker within that zero-burden subset
- non-zero-burden candidates must not be selected

### 2. Rotation only applies when inconvenience is unavoidable
Only when zero-burden candidates do not exist may the scheduler begin distributing inconvenience across weeks.

### 3. Hard boundaries remain absolute
Hard no-time boundaries remain the only hard constraint.
This rule does not weaken or reinterpret hard boundary behavior.

### 4. Working hours remain soft globally, but zero-burden is a priority state
Working hours are still modeled as soft constraints in general scoring.
However, if a candidate keeps all members inside working hours and produces zero burden for all, that candidate class has strict priority over all burden-producing candidates.

### 5. Determinism is mandatory
Given identical inputs, the scheduler must return identical outputs.
Any tie-breaking inside the zero-burden subset must remain deterministic.

---

## Beam Search / Candidate Pruning Rule

Any beam search, topK pruning, candidate filtering, or fallback search path must preserve the zero-burden priority rule.

This means:
- no pruning step may remove zero-burden candidates before they are evaluated against burden-producing candidates
- if topK is used, candidate ordering must ensure zero-burden options are considered first
- fallback and forced search paths must follow the same rule, not just the main path

If a search path can exclude zero-burden candidates because of ordering, slicing, or ranking before burden-aware evaluation, that is a blocking bug.

---

## UI / Explanation Rule

If zero-burden overlap exists, UI and explanation must reflect that reality.

### Required behavior:
- the selected schedule should come from the zero-burden subset
- the explanation must not imply unavoidable sacrifice if none exists
- if additional equally comfortable options exist, those options must be real computed alternatives, not mock/static/demo data

### Suggestion chips:
Any “other equally comfortable options” UI must:
- use real computed candidates
- respect IANA timezones
- respect DST
- respect duration
- respect hard no-times
- respect working hours
- exclude the currently selected time
- be deterministic and deduplicated

Mock, seed, placeholder, or dead-data suggestion chips are not allowed in production scheduling UI.

---

## Regression Requirements

Any scheduling change must be checked against these invariant scenarios:

### Scenario A — Full shared overlap exists
If a team has one or more zero-burden shared times, output must come from that set.

### Scenario B — No full shared overlap exists
If no zero-burden option exists, fairness rotation may distribute inconvenience.

### Scenario C — Hard boundary conflict
No candidate may violate hard no-times even if it would otherwise reduce burden.

### Scenario D — DST-sensitive overlap
Zero-burden detection must still work across DST changes using IANA timezones.

### Scenario E — Main path / fallback path parity
Main search, fallback search, and forced search must all preserve zero-burden-first behavior.

---

## Change Control

When modifying scheduling logic:
- make the smallest safe localized change
- do not refactor unrelated scoring or fairness logic
- do not rename tested functions unless necessary
- explicitly identify every path where candidate pruning happens
- document before/after behavior
- run regression checks before and after the change

Any change that allows fairness or beam pruning to override an available zero-burden option is a regression.
